  abstract = {Microtubules are highly conserved, cytoskeletal structures critical for mitosis, intracellular trafficking, and cellular morphogenesis. Single microtubule polymers form an oriented lattice of subunits that direct molecules along a vectoral path. The organization of microtubules into higher order array patterns allows cells to accomplish complex tasks ranging from chromosome segregation to extracellular matrix patterning. Unlike animal and fungal cells, flowering plants do not organize microtubules using a central organeller body such as a centrosome. Most microtubules are created at the cell cortex and remain laterally attached to the plasma membrane during the nonmitotic phase of the cell cycle. These cortical microtubules take on a significant role in plant morphogenesis, determining the sites where cellulose synthase complexes are inserted into the plasma membrane and guiding the synthase complexes during cellulose deposition. While models are taking shape for cellulose synthase interactions with microtubules, the fundamental rules governing microtubule dynamics and the broader question of how cells specify microtubule array patterns are just entering the realm of molecular mechanism. In this Update, we focus on new discoveries that are improving our understanding of how the cortical microtubules in flowering plants are created and organized to form functional array patterns.},
